[[sn:Shuto]] [[ja:衆徒]] [[ja:神人]] [[ja:境内都市]] [[ja:延暦寺]] [[ja:祇園社]] [[ja:八坂神社]] [[ja:興福寺]] [[ja:アジール]] [[ja:源義経]] [[ja:後醍醐天皇]] [[ja:検断不入]] [[ja:戦国時代]] [[ja:織田信長]] [[ja:豊臣秀吉]] [[ja:安土城]] [[ja:根来寺]] [[ja:刀狩令]] [[ja:比叡山]] [[ja:日吉大社]] [[ja:清水寺]] [[ja:石清水八幡宮]] [[ja:四天王寺]] [[ja:東大寺]] [[ja:一向宗]] [[ja:浄土真宗本願寺派]] [[ja:石山本願寺]] [[ja:山科本願寺]] [[ja:尾山御坊]] [[ja:吉崎御坊]] [[ja:一向一揆]] [[ja:専修寺]] [[ja:真宗高田派]] [[ja:金峯山寺]] [[ja:醍醐寺]] [[ja:金剛峯寺]] [[ja:高野山]] [[ja:熊野三山]] [[ja:聖護院]] [[ja:園城寺]] [[ja:出羽三山]] [[ja:平泉寺]] [[ja:平泉寺白山神社]] [[ja:石動山]] [[ja:伊須流岐比古神社]] [[ja:多武峰]] [[ja:談山神社]] [[ja:大山寺]] [[ja:諏訪大社]] [[ja:厳島神社]] [[ja:宗像大社]] [[ja:宇佐神宮]] [[ja:阿蘇神社]] [[ja:英彦山]] [[ja:黒田俊雄]] [[ja:伊藤正敏]] [[ja:顕密体制]] [[ja:権門体制]] [[ja:寺内町]] [[ja:僧兵]] [[sn:huto]] [[ja:寺社勢力]] [[en:Shuto]]

'''Shuto''' (衆徒, しゅと), also known as '''Dōshu''' (堂衆, どうしゅ/どうしゅう), originally refers to the class of Buddhist monks who, from the Heian period onward, resided in large temples and, in addition to engaging in scholarly study and ascetic training, performed the practical administrative duties within the temple. They formed the main body of the temple’s "great multitude" ({{ill|Daisū|ja|大衆|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisū|qq=}}), and in some contexts the term "daisū" is used exclusively to refer to these shuto. In particular, at {{ill|Kōfuku-ji|ja|興福寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōfuku-ji|qq=}} in {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|大和国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Province|qq=}}, where the temple also served a protective function ({{ill|Shugo|ja|守護職|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shugo|qq=}}), the warriors of the country (referred to as ''Yamato Bushi'' (大和武士)) were sometimes called shuto.
== Overview == In general, shuto Rank below the scholarly monks ({{ill|Gakuryo|ja|学侶|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gakuryo|qq=}}) and above the itinerant monks ({{ill|Gyōnin|ja|行人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gyōnin|qq=}}). They handled practical tasks within the temple such as security, management, and overall operations. Many shuto came from mid-to-lower class aristocratic families, samurai, or local officials ({{ill|Shōkan|ja|荘官|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkan|qq=}}), and some possessed martial skills; indeed, armed monk soldiers ({{ill|Sōhei|ja|僧兵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōhei|qq=}}) were largely composed of shuto. (However, at {{ill|Enryaku-ji|ja|延暦寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enryaku-ji|qq=}}, the shuto were predominantly drawn from higher-Ranking nobles, and in that temple those expelled from the shuto class organized separately as "dōshu.") They played a central role in temple decision-making and in the enforcement of the temple’s authority (through bodies such as the {{ill|Daisū Shingi|ja|大衆僉議|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisū Shingi|qq=}} and {{ill|Kyōso|ja|強訴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyōso|qq=}}). Later, as monastic hierarchies became more differentiated, scholarly monks ({{ill|Gakuryo|ja|学侶|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gakuryo|qq=}}) who were of high-Ranking court families ({{ill|Kōkei|ja|Kugyō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōkei|qq=}}) attempted to monopolize key positions and to influence temple management, leading to fierce opposition from the itinerant monks.
== Yamato Warriors == In Yamato Province, where {{ill|Kōfuku-ji|ja|興福寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōfuku-ji|qq=}} had strong connections with the {{ill|Sesseki family|ja|摂関家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sesseki family|qq=}}, the temple, upon entering the Kamakura period, eventually secured control over Nara and later over the entire Yamato region. Originally, the shuto of this temple were fixed at twenty by the imperial edict (via the {{ill|Taihōkanfu|ja|太政官符|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taihōkanfu|qq=}}), serving as assistants to the bettō and the Sangkō. Over time, however, influential temple families ({{ill|Monzeki|ja|門跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monzeki|qq=}}) such as those affiliated with {{ill|Ichijō-in|ja|一乗院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichijō-in|qq=}} and {{ill|Daijō-in|ja|大乗院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daijō-in|qq=}} expanded their power by incorporating domestic warriors and local chieftains (often styled as {{ill|Gokenin|ja|御家人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gokenin|qq=}}) into their own retinues, subsequently leading their scholarly monks to assume administrative and security roles within the temple and in the judicial matters ({{ill|Kendan|ja|検断|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kendan|qq=}}) of Nara. Additionally, through the syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism, the "divine men" ({{ill|Shinjin|ja|神人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinjin|qq=}}) of Kasuga Shrine, which had become integrated with Kōfuku-ji, were similarly incorporated, and these Kasuga deities came to be known as "kokumin" (国民).
