d, while in Ido, the Tutsui and Toshichi factions prevailed; the rivalry between the Tutsui and Ochi factions eventually split Yamato into two, sparking the conflict known as the "Yamato Eikyō no Ran." In August of the 3rd year of the {{ill|Bunmei era|ja|文明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunmei era|qq=}} (1471), forces led by Fuse (Eastern faction) and Ochi Ie Saka (Western faction) clashed—with Fuse supported by Hashio, Narahara, Kubishira, Toshichi, Tutsui, and Maetaka (Fuse Takada), and Ochi reinforced by Manzai, Hatta, Iitaka, Furuichi, Todata, Koizumi, and Tōtakada (Tōma Takada). With influential guardian daimyō also intervening, the long internal conflict, interspersed with the Ōnin War, eventually ushered in a period of warlord rule during the Sengoku period in Yamato Province.
