== Overview == In general, shuto Rank below the scholarly monks ({{ill|Gakuryo|ja|学侶|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gakuryo|qq=}}) and above the itinerant monks ({{ill|Gyōnin|ja|行人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gyōnin|qq=}}). They handled practical tasks within the temple such as security, management, and overall operations. Many shuto came from mid-to-lower class aristocratic families, samurai, or local officials ({{ill|Shōkan|ja|荘官|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkan|qq=}}), and some possessed martial skills; indeed, armed monk soldiers ({{ill|Sōhei|ja|僧兵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōhei|qq=}}) were largely composed of shuto. (However, at {{ill|Enryaku-ji|ja|延暦寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enryaku-ji|qq=}}, the shuto were predominantly drawn from higher-Ranking nobles, and in that temple those expelled from the shuto class organized separately as "dōshu.") They played a central role in temple decision-making and in the enforcement of the temple’s authority (through bodies such as the {{ill|Daisū Shingi|ja|大衆僉議|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisū Shingi|qq=}} and {{ill|Kyōso|ja|強訴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyōso|qq=}}). Later, as monastic hierarchies became more differentiated, scholarly monks ({{ill|Gakuryo|ja|学侶|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gakuryo|qq=}}) who were of high-Ranking court families ({{ill|Kōkei|ja|Kugyō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōkei|qq=}}) attempted to monopolize key positions and to influence temple management, leading to fierce opposition from the itinerant monks.
== Yamato Warriors == In Yamato Province, where {{ill|Kōfuku-ji|ja|興福寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōfuku-ji|qq=}} had strong connections with the {{ill|Sesseki family|ja|摂関家|1=Five regent houses|2=ja|3=摂家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sesseki family|qq=}}, the temple, upon entering the Kamakura period, eventually secured control over Nara and later over the entire Yamato region. Originally, the shuto of this temple were fixed at twenty by the imperial edict (via the {{ill|Taihōkanfu|ja|太政官符|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taihōkanfu|qq=}}), serving as assistants to the bettō and the Sangkō. Over time, however, influential temple families ({{ill|Monzeki|ja|門跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monzeki|qq=}}) such as those affiliated with {{ill|Ichijō-in|ja|一乗院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichijō-in|qq=}} and {{ill|Daijō-in|ja|大乗院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daijō-in|qq=}} expanded their power by incorporating domestic warriors and local chieftains (often styled as {{ill|Gokenin|ja|御家人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gokenin|qq=}}) into their own retinues, subsequently leading their scholarly monks to assume administrative and security roles within the temple and in the judicial matters ({{ill|Kendan|ja|検断|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kendan|qq=}}) of Nara. Additionally, through the syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism, the "divine men" ({{ill|Shinjin|ja|神人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinjin|qq=}}) of Kasuga Shrine, which had become integrated with Kōfuku-ji, were similarly incorporated, and these Kasuga deities came to be known as "kokumin" (国民).
Notable Yamato shuto include those under the patronage of Ichijō-in—such as members of the {{ill|Tutsui Clan|ja|筒井氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tutsui Clan|qq=}} and the {{ill|Ochi Clan|ja|越智氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ochi Clan|qq=}}—and those under Daijō-in—such as members of the {{ill|Toshichi Clan|ja|十市氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toshichi Clan|qq=}} and the {{ill|Furuichi Clan|ja|古市氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Furuichi Clan|qq=}}. In the Nanboku-chō period, Tōshichi Tōyasu invaded Kōfuku-ji’s estates and established his own domain as a local lord. In response to a request from the bettō of Kōfuku-ji for the suppression of Tōshichi Tōyasu, the 3rd shogun of the Muromachi Bakufu, {{ill|Ashikaga Yoshimitsu|ja|足利義満|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikaga Yoshimitsu|qq=}}, dispatched commanders such as {{ill|Shiba Yoshishiro|ja|斯波義将|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiba Yoshishiro|qq=}} and {{ill|Toki Yoriyasu|ja|土岐頼康|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toki Yoriyasu|qq=}} to Yamato in 1379 (Eiwa 5). However, when the Bakufu army showed no signs of commencing an expedition against Tōshichi Tōyasu, Yoshimitsu ordered all the generals of the Tōshichi suppression force to return to Kyoto. Consequently, for the first time in history, the protest by the "Jinboku Nyūroku" (the entry of the sacred tree into the capital) failed, dealing a severe blow to temple power. The 6th shogun, {{ill|Ashikaga Yoshinori|ja|足利義教|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikaga Yoshinori|qq=}}, intervened in the personnel decisions of the influential temple families within Yamato Province in order to establish Bakufu authority. However, due to conflicts between the factions of Tōdaichū-bō and Ido, the situation devolved into a quagmire. In Tōdaichū-bō, factions including Ochi, Hashio, and Manzai allied with Southern Court elements such as Sawa and Akiyama emerged, while in Ido, the Tutsui and Toshichi factions prevailed; the rivalry between the Tutsui and Ochi factions eventually split Yamato into two, sparking the conflict known as the "Yamato Eikyō no Ran." In August of the 3rd year of the {{ill|Bunmei era|ja|文明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunmei era|qq=}} (1471), forces led by Fuse (Eastern faction) and Ochi Ie Saka (Western faction) clashed—with Fuse supported by Hashio, Narahara, Kubishira, Toshichi, Tutsui, and Maetaka (Fuse Takada), and Ochi reinforced by Manzai, Hatta, Iitaka, Furuichi, Todata, Koizumi, and Tōtakada (Tōma Takada). With influential guardian daimyō also intervening, the long internal conflict, interspersed with the Ōnin War, eventually ushered in a period of warlord rule during the Sengoku period in Yamato Province.
During the Sengoku period, following the death in battle of [[Hatakeyama clan]] retainer [[Kizawa Nagamasa]] in Kawachi Province, the clans led by {{ill|Tutsui Junshō|ja|筒井氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tutsui Junshō|qq=}} and {{ill|Ochi Clan|ja|越智氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ochi Clan|qq=}} expanded their influence. For a time they controlled much of the country and advanced toward becoming warlords, but after Junshō’s sudden death and the succession by his young heir, {{ill|Tutsui Junnin|ja|十市遠康|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tutsui Junnin|qq=}}, the Ochi and Furuichi clans counterattacked, leading to the disintegration of Tutsui control. Seizing the opportunity, Matsunaga Hisahide, under the Southern Court during the Nanboku-chō period, invaded Yamato and expelled Junnin, subduing the Ochi clan and others, and in the 2nd year of the {{ill|Eiroku era|ja|永和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eiroku era|qq=}} (1559) seized the position of provincial protector (Shugo) from Kōfuku-ji. Later, under the Toyotomi regime, Tutsui Junnin reemerged as a warlord in Yamato Province and established a dual system whereby he simultaneously held the status of protector of Yamato Province and acted as the representative of the government-appointed (kanfu) shuto—the temple retainer class—in administering and safeguarding the temple. However, after Junnin's death, Toyotomi Hideyoshi granted Yamato Province to his brother Hidechō, thereby disbanding the existing system, forcing the shuto and the local "kokumin" (the people of the country) to be dissolved; and for Kōfuku-ji, only the original twenty names (as recorded on the official kanfu shuto list) were allowed to serve as temple administrators and security personnel, with a total stipend of 380 koku. == See Also == * {{ill|Yamato Eikyō no Ran|ja|大和永享の乱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Eikyō no Ran|qq=}} * {{ill|Warrior Monk|ja|ウォリアーモンク|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Warrior Monk|qq=}}
