[[sn:Shuto]] [[ja:衆徒]] [[ja:神人]] [[ja:境内都市]] [[ja:延暦寺]] [[ja:祇園社]] [[ja:八坂神社]] [[ja:興福寺]] [[ja:アジール]] [[ja:源義経]] [[ja:後醍醐天皇]] [[ja:検断不入]] [[ja:戦国時代]] [[ja:織田信長]] [[ja:豊臣秀吉]] [[ja:安土城]] [[ja:根来寺]] [[ja:刀狩令]] [[ja:比叡山]] [[ja:日吉大社]] [[ja:清水寺]] [[ja:石清水八幡宮]] [[ja:四天王寺]] [[ja:東大寺]] [[ja:一向宗]] [[ja:浄土真宗本願寺派]] [[ja:石山本願寺]] [[ja:山科本願寺]] [[ja:尾山御坊]] [[ja:吉崎御坊]] [[ja:一向一揆]] [[ja:専修寺]] [[ja:真宗高田派]] [[ja:金峯山寺]] [[ja:醍醐寺]] [[ja:金剛峯寺]] [[ja:高野山]] [[ja:熊野三山]] [[ja:聖護院]] [[ja:園城寺]] [[ja:出羽三山]] [[ja:平泉寺]] [[ja:平泉寺白山神社]] [[ja:石動山]] [[ja:伊須流岐比古神社]] [[ja:多武峰]] [[ja:談山神社]] [[ja:大山寺]] [[ja:諏訪大社]] [[ja:厳島神社]] [[ja:宗像大社]] [[ja:宇佐神宮]] [[ja:阿蘇神社]] [[ja:英彦山]] [[ja:黒田俊雄]] [[ja:伊藤正敏]] [[ja:顕密体制]] [[ja:権門体制]] [[ja:寺内町]] [[ja:僧兵]] [[sn:huto]] [[ja:寺社勢力]] [[en:Shuto]] [[Category:Monks]] [[Category:translated pages with valid en interwikis]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis--> <!--enwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[Category:pages without english wikidata name]] [[sn:Shuto]][[en:Shuto]] {{wikidata link|Q11625971}}

{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[Category:Has wikidata]][[d:Q11625971]] Wikidata name: [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 09:29, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} '''Shuto''' (衆徒, しゅと), also known as '''Dōshu''' (堂衆, どうしゅ/どうしゅう), originally refers to the class of Buddhist monks who, from the Heian period onward, resided in large temples and, in addition to engaging in scholarly study and ascetic training, performed the practical administrative duties within the temple. They formed the main body of the temple’s "great multitude" ({{ill|Daisū|ja|大衆|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisū|qq=|1=general public|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q5369389}}), and in some contexts the term "daisū" is used exclusively to refer to these shuto. In particular, at [[:en:Kōfuku-ji|Kōfuku-ji]] in [[:en:Yamato Province|Yamato Province]], where the temple also served a protective function ({{ill|Shugo|ja|守護職|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shugo|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 守護|1=shugo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1141023}}), the warriors of the country (referred to as ''Yamato Bushi'' (大和武士)) were sometimes called shuto.
== Overview == In general, shuto Rank below the scholarly monks ({{ill|Gakuryo|ja|学侶|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gakuryo|qq=|1=Gakuryo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11448122}}) and above the itinerant monks ([[:en:The Wayfarer (novel)|Gyōnin]]). They handled practical tasks within the temple such as security, management, and overall operations. Many shuto came from mid-to-lower class aristocratic families, samurai, or local officials ({{ill|Shōkan|ja|荘官|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkan|qq=|1=shōkan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11618914}}), and some possessed martial skills; indeed, armed monk soldiers ([[:en:Sōhei|Sōhei]]) were largely composed of shuto. (However, at [[:en:Enryaku-ji|Enryaku-ji]], the shuto were predominantly drawn from higher-Ranking nobles, and in that temple those expelled from the shuto class organized separately as "dōshu.") They played a central role in temple decision-making and in the enforcement of the temple’s authority (through bodies such as the {{ill|Daisū Shingi|ja|大衆僉議|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisū Shingi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and {{ill|Kyōso|ja|強訴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyōso|qq=|1=gōso|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11487759}}). Later, as monastic hierarchies became more differentiated, scholarly monks ({{ill|Gakuryo|ja|学侶|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gakuryo|qq=|1=Gakuryo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11448122}}) who were of high-Ranking court families ({{ill|Kōkei|ja|Kugyō|1=kugyō|2=ja|3=公卿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōkei|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q3138036}}) attempted to monopolize key positions and to influence temple management, leading to fierce opposition from the itinerant monks.
